ce:section.ce:para:
To further evaluate the feasibility of CDs for potential bioimaging applications, CDs surface was modified with folic acid.The probable mechanism of CDs conjugation with folic acid was shown in Fig. S4 (supporting materials). Folate/folic acid is vital for many cell functioning and these receptors are found in high concentrations in numerous cancer cells. Accordingly, the folic acid/folate receptor interface was usually targeted for imaging cancer cells via conjugation with CDs [47]. EDC/NHS based carbodiimide coupling was widely used to covalently conjugate surface functional groups (amine/carboxylic) of nanomaterials with folic acid. Upon the addition of EDS-NHS with MES to CDs, it activates the carboxylic acid group on the surface to interact with the amine group of folic acid enables the formation of amide linkage [48,49].The conjugation of folic acid with CDs (FA-CDs) was confirmed by UV–vis and fluorescence spectroscopic analysis (Fig.S5,supporting materials). Compared to CDs, the FA-CDs showed a shift in absorption peak from 280 nm to 270 nm and the peak at 350 nm was not observed. The peak at 270 nm is corresponding to the pterin rings of folic acid [50]. The FA-CDs showed an increased zeta potential of -16.54 ± 1.59 mV which further confirmed the successful conjugation of folic acid [33,51–53]. The FA-CDs showed an increased zeta potential of -16.54 ± 1.59 mV which further confirmed the successful conjugation of folic acid (Fig.S2 B). Further, the conjugation of FA did not affect the fluorescence of CDs, i.e. the fluorescence of CDs did not show any quenching after the folic acid conjugation. FA-CDs were also brightly fluorescent with excitation wavelength-dependent emission similar to CDs. Fig S6 shows the optical images captured under normal and UV light for CDs and FA-CDs at 0 h and 48 h. Similarly, Fig S7, represents the flourescene spectra of CDs and FA -CDs at a regular intervals for 48 h. FA-CDs also exhibited significant photostability. In order to utilize CDs as fluorescent probes for multi-color bio-imaging, it is important to study their toxicity and biocompatibility in cancer and normal cells respectively. The L929 cells (mouse fibroblast cells) were used to evaluate the cytotoxicity of the CDs by the 3-(4,5-dimethylthiazol-2-yl)-2,5-diphenyltetrazolium bromide (MTT) assay (Fig. 6
                        ). The CDs exhibited tremendously low cytotoxicity with cells retaining the viability of about 95% even at a concentration of 1 mg/mL. These results show the excellent biocompatibility of CDs. To study the multi-color bio-imaging of cells, we further introduced the CDs and FA-CDs to breast cancer cells (MCF-7) and illuminated by bright light, UV light (330−385 nm), blue light (450−480 nm), and green light (510−550 nm). As seen in Fig. 7
                        , there is no noticeable emission from the control cells without CDs or FA-CDs. Whereas, MCF-7 cells treated with CDs showed noticeable fluorescence in different colors depending on excitation. However, the MCF-7 cells treated with FA-CDs showed bright fluorescence respective to excitations. Folic acid conjugation is reported to enhance cellular uptake in cancer cells and thereby a stronger fluorescent signal was observed in cells. Therefore, the selectivity of CDs to approach the tumor cells becomes more targeted after conjugation with folic acid which improves the cellular uptake resulting in enhanced fluorescence emission of FA-CDs compared to CDs. The MCF-7 cells treated with FA-CDs showed bright fluorescent emission than CDs treated cells under microscopy indicating that FA-CDs are remarkable materials for cellular imaging applications.
